{"title_page": "Trans-Allegheny Lunatic Asylum", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP\n|name=Weston State Hospital <!-- This is the official NRHP name-->\n|nrhp_type=nhl\n|image=Weston State Hospital.jpg\n|caption=The Hospital's main building in 2006\n|location=Asylum Drive, [[Weston, West Virginia]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|39|02|19|N|80|28|17|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = West Virginia#USA\n|built=Constructed 1858-1881. Opened to patients 1864.\n|architect=[[Richard Snowden Andrews]]\n|architecture=[[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival]]<br>[[Tudorbethan architecture|Tudor Revival]]<br>[[Kirkbride Plan]]\n|designated_nrhp_type=June 21, 1990<ref name=\"nhlsum\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1791&ResourceType=Building\n |title       = Weston Hospital Main Building\n |accessdate  = 2007-10-13\n |work        = National Historic Landmark summary listing\n |publisher   = National Park Service\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080328041110/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1791&ResourceType=Building\n |archivedate = 2008-03-28\n}}</ref>\n|added=April 19, 1978<ref name=nris/> \n  | area = {{convert|26.5|acre}}\n  | governing_body = State   \n  | refnum = 78002805<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Trans-Allegheny Lunatic Asylum''', subsequently the '''Weston State Hospital''', was a [[Kirkbride Plan|Kirkbride]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kirkbridebuildings.com/buildings/weston/|title=Weston State Hospital - Kirkbride Buildings|website=www.kirkbridebuildings.com}}</ref> [[psychiatric hospital]] that was operated from 1864 until 1994 by the government of the [[U.S. state]] of [[West Virginia]], in the city of [[Weston, West Virginia|Weston]]. '''Weston State Hospital''' got its name in 1913 which was used while patients occupied it, but was changed back to its originally commissioned, unused name, the '''Trans-Allegheny Lunatic Asylum''', after being reopened as a tourist attraction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvencyclopedia.org/timelines/1148/list|title=Weston State Hospital|last=Gerald|first=Swick|date=28 September 2015|website=The West Virginia Encyclopedia|access-date=12 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDesigned by Gothic Revival and Tudor Revival styles by Baltimore architect [[Richard Snowden Andrews]], it was constructed from 1858\u20131881. <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://abandonedonline.net/location/trans-allegheny-lunatic-asylum/|title=Trans-Allegheny Lunatic Asylum|last=Cahal|first=Sherman|date=2019-07-05|website=Abandoned|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-10}}</ref> Originally designed to hold 250 people, it became overcrowded in the 1950s with 2,400 patients. It was forcibly closed in 1994 due to changes in patient treatment. The hospital was bought by Joe Jordan in 2007, and is opened for tours and other events to raise money for its restoration.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Old asylums decay, while some strive for restoration\n|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/nation/bal-te.asylums03aug03,0,7632214.story\n|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]\n|date=2008-08-03\n|accessdate=2008-08-03}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The hospital's main building is claimed to be one of the largest hand-cut [[stonemasonry|stone masonry]] buildings in the United States,<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Nickell |first=Joe |authorlink=Joe Nickell |date=November-December 2019 |title=Haunted Asylums: Imagining Scary Ghosts |url=https://skepticalinquirer.org/2019/11/haunted-asylums-imagining-scary-ghosts/ |magazine=[[Skeptical Inquirer]] |publisher=[[Center for Inquiry]] |volume=43 |issue=6 |pages=20-23 |archive-url=http://archive.is/wT7rI |archive-date=1 April 2020 |access-date=1 April 2020 }}</ref> and the second largest hand-cut sandstone building in the world, with the only bigger one being in the [[Moscow Kremlin]]. As '''Weston Hospital Main Building''', it was designated a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1990.<ref name=\"nhlsum\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1791&ResourceType=Building\n |title       = Weston Hospital Main Building\n |accessdate  = 2007-10-13\n |work        = National Historic Landmark summary listing\n |publisher   = National Park Service\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080328041110/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1791&ResourceType=Building\n |archivedate = 2008-03-28\n}}</ref><ref name=\"nrhpinv2\">{{Cite journal|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: Weston Hospital Main Building / The Lunatic Asylym West of the Alleghany Mountains / West Virginia Hospital for the Insane|url={{NHLS url|id=78002805}} |format=pdf|date=January 10, 1990 |author=West Virginia SHPO and Carolyn Pitts |publisher=National Park Service}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===19th century===\nThe hospital was authorized by the [[Virginia General Assembly]] in the early 1850s as the Trans-[[Allegheny Mountains|Allegheny]] Lunatic Asylum.<ref name=WVenc>{{cite book| last= Swick |first= Gerald D. |editor= Ken Sullivan| title= The West Virginia Encyclopedia |year= 2006 |publisher= West Virginia Humanities Council |location=Charleston, W.Va. |isbn= 0-9778498-0-5 |pages= 779 |chapter=Weston State Hospital}}</ref>  Following consultations with [[Thomas Story Kirkbride]], then-superintendent of the [[The Institute of the Pennsylvania Hospital|Pennsylvania Hospital for the Insane]], a building in the [[Kirkbride Plan]]<ref name=WHRChist>{{cite web|url=http://www.westonlandmark.com/history.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20010713141751/http://www.westonlandmark.com/history.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2001-07-13 |title=Hospital History |author=Weston Hospital Revitalization Committee |year=2005 |accessdate=2007-02-15 }}</ref> was designed in the [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival]] and [[Tudorbethan architecture|Tudor Revival]] styles by [[Richard Snowden Andrews]] (1830\u20131903),<ref name=nris/><ref name=WVenc/> an architect from [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]] whose other commissions included the [[Government House (Maryland)|Maryland Governor's residence]] in [[Annapolis, Maryland|Annapolis]] and the south wing of the [[United States Department of the Treasury|U.S. Treasury building]] in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]].<ref name=WVnrhp>{{cite book |title= Historic West Virginia: The National Register of Historic Places |year=2000 |publisher=West Virginia Division of Culture and History: State Historic Preservation Office |location= Charleston, W.Va. |pages= 74\u201375}}</ref>  Construction on the site, along the [[West Fork River]] opposite downtown Weston, began in late 1858.  Work was initially conducted by [[penal labour|prison laborers]]; a local newspaper in November of that year noted \"seven convict [[negro]]es\" as the first arrivals for work on the project.  Skilled stonemasons were later brought in from [[Germany]] and [[Ireland]].<ref name=WHRChist/>\n\nConstruction was interrupted by the outbreak of the [[American Civil War]] in 1861.  Following its secession from the United States, the government of Virginia demanded the return of the hospital's unused construction funds for its defense. Before this could occur, the [[7th Ohio Infantry|7th Ohio Volunteer Infantry]] seized the money from a local bank, delivering it to [[Wheeling, West Virginia|Wheeling]]. It was put towards the establishment of the [[Wheeling Convention|Reorganized Government of Virginia]], which sided with the northern states during the war.  The Reorganized Government appropriated money to resume construction in 1862. Following the admission of West Virginia as a U.S. state in 1863, the hospital was renamed the West Virginia Hospital for the Insane.  The first patients were admitted in October 1864, but construction continued into 1881.  The 200-foot (61 m)<ref name=WHRCnews>{{cite web|url=http://www.westonlandmark.com/news.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20010813164408/http://www.westonlandmark.com/news.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2001-08-13 |title=Hospital News |author=Weston Hospital Revitalization Committee |year=2005 |accessdate=2007-02-19 }}</ref> central clock tower was completed in 1871, and separate rooms for [[African American|black people]] were completed in 1873.<ref name=WVenc/><ref name=WHRChist/><ref name=WVnrhp/>  The hospital was intended to be self-sufficient,<ref name=WVnrhp/> and a farm, dairy, [[water supply|waterworks]], and cemetery were located on its grounds,<ref name=WVenc/> which ultimately reached {{convert|666|acre|ha|lk=out}} in area.\n\n===20th century===\nA [[natural gas|gas]] well was drilled on the hospital grounds in 1902.<ref name=WHRChist/>  Its name was again changed to Weston State Hospital in 1913.<ref name=WVenc/>\n\nOriginally designed to house 250 patients in solitude, the hospital held 717 patients by 1880; 1,661 in 1938; over 1,800 in 1949; at its peak, 2,600 in the 1950s in overcrowded conditions.  A 1938 report by a survey committee organized by a group of North American medical organizations found that the hospital housed \"[[epilepsy|epileptics]], [[alcoholism|alcoholics]], [[drug addiction|drug addicts]] and non-educable mental defectives\" among its population.  A series of reports by ''[[The Charleston Gazette]]'' in 1949 found poor sanitation and insufficient furniture, lighting, and heating in  much of the complex, while one wing, which had been rebuilt using [[Works Progress Administration]] funds following a 1935 fire started by a patient, was comparatively luxurious.<ref name=WHRChist/>\n\nWeston State Hospital found itself to be the home for the West Virginia Lobotomy Project in the early 1950s. This was an effort by the state of West Virginia and Walter Freeman to use lobotomy to reduce the number of patients in asylums because there was severe overcrowding. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=American Lobotomy: A Rhetorical History|last=Johnson|first=Jenell|publisher=University of Michigan Press|year=|isbn=978-0-472-03665-3|location=|pages=152, 162, 164\u2013165, 168\u2013169}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBy the 1980s, the hospital had a reduced population due to changes in the treatment of mental illness. Those patients who could not be controlled were often locked in cages.  In February 1986, then-Governor [[Arch A. Moore, Jr.|Arch Moore]] announced plans to build a new psychiatric facility elsewhere in the state and convert the Weston hospital to a prison. <ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=WHRChist/> Ultimately the new facility, the William R. Sharpe Jr. Hospital, was built in Weston and the old Weston State Hospital was simply closed in May 1994.<ref name=WVenc/>  The building and its grounds have since been mostly vacant, aside from local events such as fairs, church revivals, and tours.<ref name=WHRChist/>  In 1999, all four floors of the interior of the building were damaged by several city and county police officers playing [[paintball]],<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.post-gazette.com/regionstate/19990620paint4.asp |title=A Town Sees Red Over Police Vandalism. |author=Post Gazette | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | date=1999-06-20}}</ref> three of whom were dismissed over the incident.\n\nEfforts towards [[adaptive reuse]] of the building have included proposals to convert the building into a Civil War Museum<ref name=WVenc/> and a hotel and golf course complex.<ref name=WHRCnews/><ref name=\":1\" />  A non-profit [[501(c)|501(c)3]] organization, the Weston Hospital Revitalization Committee, was formed in 2000 for the purpose of aiding the preservation of the building and finding appropriate tenants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westonlandmark.com/about_whrc.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20061120102548/http://www.westonlandmark.com/about_whrc.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2006-11-20 |title=About WHRC |author=Weston Hospital Revitalization Committee |year=2005 |accessdate=2007-02-19 }}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===21st century===\nThree small museums devoted to military history, toys, and mental health were opened on the first floor of the main hospital building in 2004, but were soon forced to close due to [[fire safety|fire code]] violations. <ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=WHRCnews/>\n\nThe hospital was auctioned by the West Virginia Department of Health and Human Resources on August 29, 2007. Joe Jordan, an asbestos demolition contractor from [[Morgantown, West Virginia|Morgantown]], was the high bidder and paid $1.5 million for the {{convert|242000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} building. Bidding started at $500,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.com/story/News/2007082978/Morgantown-contractor-buys-old-Weston-State-Hospital/ |title=Morgantown contractor buys old Weston State Hospital |newspaper=Charleston Daily Mail |accessdate=2007-08-29 }}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Joe Jordan has also begun maintenance projects on the former hospital grounds. In October 2007, a Fall Fest was held at the Weston State Hospital. Guided historic and paranormal daytime tours were offered as well as evening ghost hunts and paranormal tours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://trans-alleghenylunaticasylum.com/main/hauntings.html|title=Paranormal tours and Ghost Hunts TRANS-ALLEGHENY LUNATIC ASYLUM|website=trans-alleghenylunaticasylum.com|access-date=2017-09-20}}</ref>\n\nThe main building of the asylum, known as the Kirkbride, holds several rooms that serve as the museum, located on the first floor. There are paintings, poems, and drawings made by patients in the art therapy programs, a room dedicated to the different medical treatments and restraints used in the past, and artifacts such as a straitjacket and hydrotherapy tub. The tour guides dress in clothes that resemble 19th century nurse outfits; blue dress, white apron, white cap, and white shoes. The shorter historical tour offer allows visitors to see the first floor of the Kirkbride, while the longer historical tour allows visitors to see all four floors, apartments of the staff, the morgue, and the operating room. Aside from the historical tours, there are also two paranormal tours. Both start as the sun sets, the shorter tour lasting around two to three hours, the longer tour being overnight with the option of having a private tour.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==In popular culture==\n*The former facility was featured as a haunted location on several paranormal television shows, including ''[[Ghost Stories (2009 TV series)|Ghost Stories]]'', [[Syfy]]'s ''[[Ghost Hunters (TV series)|Ghost Hunters]]'', [[Travel Channel]]'s ''[[Ghost Adventures]]'', and ''[[Paranormal Lockdown]]'' on [[Destination America]]/[[The Learning Channel|TLC]] as well as ''[[Portals To Hell]]''\n*The facility is featured in [[Bethesda Game Studios]]' 2018 video game ''[[Fallout 76]]'', under the name \u201cFort Defiance\u201d, acting as a base for The Brotherhood of Steel, one of the game's main factions.\n*The facility is featured in episode 60 of the podcast ''[[Lore (podcast)|Lore]]''.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of National Historic Landmarks by state|List of National Historic Landmarks]]\n*[[List of Registered Historic Places in West Virginia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Weston State Hospital}}\n* {{official website|http://www.trans-alleghenylunaticasylum.com/}}\n*[http://www.vimeo.com/kirkbrideshd/weston High Definition video from Kirkbrides HD]\n*[http://abandonedonline.net/location/trans-allegheny-lunatic-asylum/ Trans-Allegheny Lunatic Asylum] at Abandoned\n* [http://arch.thomas-industriesinc.com/Bldg_WestonState.htm Trans-Allegheny Lunatic Asylum] at Architecture of the State\n*[http://www.asylumprojects.org/index.php?title=Weston_State_Hospital Trans-Allegheny Lunatic Asylum] at Asylum Projects\n* [http://www.kirkbridebuildings.com/buildings/weston/ Trans-Allegheny Lunatic Asylum] at Kirkbride Buildings\n* [https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/2132404/weston-state-hospital-cemetery Weston State Hospital Cemetery interments] at [[Find-a-Grave]]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n{{Kirkbride Plan}}\n\n[[Category:1864 establishments in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:1994 disestablishments in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1881]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Lewis County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Defunct hospitals in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Gothic Revival architecture in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Kirkbride Plan hospitals]]\n[[Category:National Historic Landmarks in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Lewis County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Psychiatric hospitals in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Reportedly haunted locations in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Tudor Revival architecture in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Works Progress Administration in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1864]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n|name=Weston State Hospital <!-- This is the official NRHP name-->\n|nrhp_type=nhl\n|image=Weston State Hospital.jpg\n|caption=The Hospital's main building in 2006\n|location=Asylum Drive, [[Weston, West Virginia]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|39|02|19|N|80|28|17|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = West Virginia#USA\n|built=Constructed 1858-1881. Opened to patients 1864.\n|architect=[[Richard Snowden Andrews]]\n|architecture=[[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival]]<br>[[Tudorbethan architecture|Tudor Revival]]<br>[[Kirkbride Plan]]\n|designated_nrhp_type=June 21, 1990<ref name=\"nhlsum\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1791&ResourceType=Building\n |title       = Weston Hospital Main Building\n |accessdate  = 2007-10-13\n |work        = National Historic Landmark summary listing\n |publisher   = National Park Service\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080328041110/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1791&ResourceType=Building\n |archivedate = 2008-03-28\n}}</ref>\n|added=April 19, 1978<ref name=nris/> \n  | area = {{convert|26.5|acre}}\n  | governing_body = State   \n  | refnum = 78002805<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Trans-Allegheny Lunatic Asylum''', subsequently the '''Weston State Hospital''', was a [[Kirkbride Plan|Kirkbride]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kirkbridebuildings.com/buildings/weston/|title=Weston State Hospital - Kirkbride Buildings|website=www.kirkbridebuildings.com}}</ref> [[psychiatric hospital]] that was operated from 1864 until 1994 by the government of the [[U.S. state]] of [[West Virginia]], in the city of [[Weston, West Virginia|Weston]]. '''Weston State Hospital''' got its name in 1913 which was used while patients occupied it, but was changed back to its originally commissioned, unused name, the '''Trans-Allegheny Lunatic Asylum''', after being reopened as a tourist attraction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvencyclopedia.org/timelines/1148/list|title=Weston State Hospital|last=Gerald|first=Swick|date=28 September 2015|website=The West Virginia Encyclopedia|access-date=12 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDesigned by Gothic Revival and Tudor Revival styles by Baltimore architect [[Richard Snowden Andrews]], it was constructed from 1858\u20131881. <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://abandonedonline.net/location/trans-allegheny-lunatic-asylum/|title=Trans-Allegheny Lunatic Asylum|last=Cahal|first=Sherman|date=2019-07-05|website=Abandoned|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-10}}</ref> Originally designed to hold 250 people, it became overcrowded in the 1950s with 2,400 patients. It was forcibly closed in 1994 due to changes in patient treatment. The hospital was bought by Joe Jordan in 2007, and is opened for tours and other events to raise money for its restoration.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Old asylums decay, while some strive for restoration\n|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/nation/bal-te.asylums03aug03,0,7632214.story\n|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]\n|date=2008-08-03\n|accessdate=2008-08-03}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The hospital's main building is claimed to be one of the largest hand-cut [[stonemasonry|stone masonry]] buildings in the United States<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Nickell |first=Joe |authorlink=Joe Nickell |date=November-December 2019 |title=Haunted Asylums: Imagining Scary Ghosts |url=https://skepticalinquirer.org/2019/11/haunted-asylums-imagining-scary-ghosts/ |magazine=[[Skeptical Inquirer]] |publisher=[[Center for Inquiry]] |volume=43 |issue=6 |pages=20-23 |archive-url=http://archive.is/wT7rI |archive-date=1 April 2020 |access-date=1 April 2020 }}</ref>, and the second largest hand-cut sandstone building in the world, with the only bigger one being in the [[Moscow Kremlin]]. As '''Weston Hospital Main Building''', it was designated a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1990.<ref name=\"nhlsum\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1791&ResourceType=Building\n |title       = Weston Hospital Main Building\n |accessdate  = 2007-10-13\n |work        = National Historic Landmark summary listing\n |publisher   = National Park Service\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080328041110/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=1791&ResourceType=Building\n |archivedate = 2008-03-28\n}}</ref><ref name=\"nrhpinv2\">{{Cite journal|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: Weston Hospital Main Building / The Lunatic Asylym West of the Alleghany Mountains / West Virginia Hospital for the Insane|url={{NHLS url|id=78002805}} |format=pdf|date=January 10, 1990 |author=West Virginia SHPO and Carolyn Pitts |publisher=National Park Service}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===19th century===\nThe hospital was authorized by the [[Virginia General Assembly]] in the early 1850s as the Trans-[[Allegheny Mountains|Allegheny]] Lunatic Asylum.<ref name=WVenc>{{cite book| last= Swick |first= Gerald D. |editor= Ken Sullivan| title= The West Virginia Encyclopedia |year= 2006 |publisher= West Virginia Humanities Council |location=Charleston, W.Va. |isbn= 0-9778498-0-5 |pages= 779 |chapter=Weston State Hospital}}</ref>  Following consultations with [[Thomas Story Kirkbride]], then-superintendent of the [[The Institute of the Pennsylvania Hospital|Pennsylvania Hospital for the Insane]], a building in the [[Kirkbride Plan]]<ref name=WHRChist>{{cite web|url=http://www.westonlandmark.com/history.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20010713141751/http://www.westonlandmark.com/history.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2001-07-13 |title=Hospital History |author=Weston Hospital Revitalization Committee |year=2005 |accessdate=2007-02-15 }}</ref> was designed in the [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival]] and [[Tudorbethan architecture|Tudor Revival]] styles by [[Richard Snowden Andrews]] (1830\u20131903),<ref name=nris/><ref name=WVenc/> an architect from [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]] whose other commissions included the [[Government House (Maryland)|Maryland Governor's residence]] in [[Annapolis, Maryland|Annapolis]] and the south wing of the [[United States Department of the Treasury|U.S. Treasury building]] in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]].<ref name=WVnrhp>{{cite book |title= Historic West Virginia: The National Register of Historic Places |year=2000 |publisher=West Virginia Division of Culture and History: State Historic Preservation Office |location= Charleston, W.Va. |pages= 74\u201375}}</ref>  Construction on the site, along the [[West Fork River]] opposite downtown Weston, began in late 1858.  Work was initially conducted by [[penal labour|prison laborers]]; a local newspaper in November of that year noted \"seven convict [[negro]]es\" as the first arrivals for work on the project.  Skilled stonemasons were later brought in from [[Germany]] and [[Ireland]].<ref name=WHRChist/>\n\nConstruction was interrupted by the outbreak of the [[American Civil War]] in 1861.  Following its secession from the United States, the government of Virginia demanded the return of the hospital's unused construction funds for its defense. Before this could occur, the [[7th Ohio Infantry|7th Ohio Volunteer Infantry]] seized the money from a local bank, delivering it to [[Wheeling, West Virginia|Wheeling]]. It was put towards the establishment of the [[Wheeling Convention|Reorganized Government of Virginia]], which sided with the northern states during the war.  The Reorganized Government appropriated money to resume construction in 1862. Following the admission of West Virginia as a U.S. state in 1863, the hospital was renamed the West Virginia Hospital for the Insane.  The first patients were admitted in October 1864, but construction continued into 1881.  The 200-foot (61 m)<ref name=WHRCnews>{{cite web|url=http://www.westonlandmark.com/news.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20010813164408/http://www.westonlandmark.com/news.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2001-08-13 |title=Hospital News |author=Weston Hospital Revitalization Committee |year=2005 |accessdate=2007-02-19 }}</ref> central clock tower was completed in 1871, and separate rooms for [[African American|black people]] were completed in 1873.<ref name=WVenc/><ref name=WHRChist/><ref name=WVnrhp/>  The hospital was intended to be self-sufficient,<ref name=WVnrhp/> and a farm, dairy, [[water supply|waterworks]], and cemetery were located on its grounds,<ref name=WVenc/> which ultimately reached {{convert|666|acre|ha|lk=out}} in area.\n\n===20th century===\nA [[natural gas|gas]] well was drilled on the hospital grounds in 1902.<ref name=WHRChist/>  Its name was again changed to Weston State Hospital in 1913.<ref name=WVenc/>\n\nOriginally designed to house 250 patients in solitude, the hospital held 717 patients by 1880; 1,661 in 1938; over 1,800 in 1949; at its peak, 2,600 in the 1950s in overcrowded conditions.  A 1938 report by a survey committee organized by a group of North American medical organizations found that the hospital housed \"[[epilepsy|epileptics]], [[alcoholism|alcoholics]], [[drug addiction|drug addicts]] and non-educable mental defectives\" among its population.  A series of reports by ''[[The Charleston Gazette]]'' in 1949 found poor sanitation and insufficient furniture, lighting, and heating in  much of the complex, while one wing, which had been rebuilt using [[Works Progress Administration]] funds following a 1935 fire started by a patient, was comparatively luxurious.<ref name=WHRChist/>\n\nWeston State Hospital found itself to be the home for the West Virginia Lobotomy Project in the early 1950s. This was an effort by the state of West Virginia and Walter Freeman to use lobotomy to reduce the number of patients in asylums because there was severe overcrowding. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=American Lobotomy: A Rhetorical History|last=Johnson|first=Jenell|publisher=University of Michigan Press|year=|isbn=978-0-472-03665-3|location=|pages=152, 162, 164\u2013165, 168\u2013169}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBy the 1980s, the hospital had a reduced population due to changes in the treatment of mental illness. Those patients who could not be controlled were often locked in cages.  In February 1986, then-Governor [[Arch A. Moore, Jr.|Arch Moore]] announced plans to build a new psychiatric facility elsewhere in the state and convert the Weston hospital to a prison. <ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=WHRChist/> Ultimately the new facility, the William R. Sharpe Jr. Hospital, was built in Weston and the old Weston State Hospital was simply closed in May 1994.<ref name=WVenc/>  The building and its grounds have since been mostly vacant, aside from local events such as fairs, church revivals, and tours.<ref name=WHRChist/>  In 1999, all four floors of the interior of the building were damaged by several city and county police officers playing [[paintball]],<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.post-gazette.com/regionstate/19990620paint4.asp |title=A Town Sees Red Over Police Vandalism. |author=Post Gazette | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | date=1999-06-20}}</ref> three of whom were dismissed over the incident.\n\nEfforts towards [[adaptive reuse]] of the building have included proposals to convert the building into a Civil War Museum<ref name=WVenc/> and a hotel and golf course complex.<ref name=WHRCnews/><ref name=\":1\" />  A non-profit [[501(c)|501(c)3]] organization, the Weston Hospital Revitalization Committee, was formed in 2000 for the purpose of aiding the preservation of the building and finding appropriate tenants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westonlandmark.com/about_whrc.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20061120102548/http://www.westonlandmark.com/about_whrc.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2006-11-20 |title=About WHRC |author=Weston Hospital Revitalization Committee |year=2005 |accessdate=2007-02-19 }}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===21st century===\nThree small museums devoted to military history, toys, and mental health were opened on the first floor of the main hospital building in 2004, but were soon forced to close due to [[fire safety|fire code]] violations. <ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=WHRCnews/>\n\nThe hospital was auctioned by the West Virginia Department of Health and Human Resources on August 29, 2007. Joe Jordan, an asbestos demolition contractor from [[Morgantown, West Virginia|Morgantown]], was the high bidder and paid $1.5 million for the {{convert|242000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} building. Bidding started at $500,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.com/story/News/2007082978/Morgantown-contractor-buys-old-Weston-State-Hospital/ |title=Morgantown contractor buys old Weston State Hospital |newspaper=Charleston Daily Mail |accessdate=2007-08-29 }}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Joe Jordan has also begun maintenance projects on the former hospital grounds. In October 2007, a Fall Fest was held at the Weston State Hospital. Guided historic and paranormal daytime tours were offered as well as evening ghost hunts and paranormal tours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://trans-alleghenylunaticasylum.com/main/hauntings.html|title=Paranormal tours and Ghost Hunts TRANS-ALLEGHENY LUNATIC ASYLUM|website=trans-alleghenylunaticasylum.com|access-date=2017-09-20}}</ref>\n\nThe main building of the asylum, known as the Kirkbride, holds several rooms that serve as the museum, located on the first floor. There are paintings, poems, and drawings made by patients in the art therapy programs, a room dedicated to the different medical treatments and restraints used in the past, and artifacts such as a straitjacket and hydrotherapy tub. The tour guides dress in clothes that resemble 19th century nurse outfits; blue dress, white apron, white cap, and white shoes. The shorter historical tour offer allows visitors to see the first floor of the Kirkbride, while the longer historical tour allows visitors to see all four floors, apartments of the staff, the morgue, and the operating room. Aside from the historical tours, there are also two paranormal tours. Both start as the sun sets, the shorter tour lasting around two to three hours, the longer tour being overnight with the option of having a private tour.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==In popular culture==\n*The former facility was featured as a haunted location on several paranormal television shows, including ''[[Ghost Stories (2009 TV series)|Ghost Stories]]'', [[Syfy]]'s ''[[Ghost Hunters (TV series)|Ghost Hunters]]'', [[Travel Channel]]'s ''[[Ghost Adventures]]'', and ''[[Paranormal Lockdown]]'' on [[Destination America]]/[[The Learning Channel|TLC]] as well as ''[[Portals To Hell]]''\n*The facility is featured in [[Bethesda Game Studios]]' 2018 video game ''[[Fallout 76]]'', under the name \u201cFort Defiance\u201d, acting as a base for The Brotherhood of Steel, one of the game's main factions.\n*The facility is featured in episode 60 of the podcast ''[[Lore (podcast)|Lore]]''.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of National Historic Landmarks by state|List of National Historic Landmarks]]\n*[[List of Registered Historic Places in West Virginia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Weston State Hospital}}\n* {{official website|http://www.trans-alleghenylunaticasylum.com/}}\n*[http://www.vimeo.com/kirkbrideshd/weston High Definition video from Kirkbrides HD]\n*[http://abandonedonline.net/location/trans-allegheny-lunatic-asylum/ Trans-Allegheny Lunatic Asylum] at Abandoned\n* [http://arch.thomas-industriesinc.com/Bldg_WestonState.htm Trans-Allegheny Lunatic Asylum] at Architecture of the State\n*[http://www.asylumprojects.org/index.php?title=Weston_State_Hospital Trans-Allegheny Lunatic Asylum] at Asylum Projects\n* [http://www.kirkbridebuildings.com/buildings/weston/ Trans-Allegheny Lunatic Asylum] at Kirkbride Buildings\n* [https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/2132404/weston-state-hospital-cemetery Weston State Hospital Cemetery interments] at [[Find-a-Grave]]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n{{Kirkbride Plan}}\n\n[[Category:1864 establishments in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:1994 disestablishments in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1881]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Lewis County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Defunct hospitals in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Gothic Revival architecture in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Kirkbride Plan hospitals]]\n[[Category:National Historic Landmarks in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Lewis County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Psychiatric hospitals in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Reportedly haunted locations in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Tudor Revival architecture in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Works Progress Administration in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1864]]\n", "name_user": "DinoBenn", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trans-Allegheny_Lunatic_Asylum"}
